  "prompt": "How long does weed stay in your blood?",
  "response": "The duration that tetrahydrocannabinol (THC), the active ingredient in marijuana (weed), stays in the bloodstream can vary based on several factors including the frequency of use, metabolism, and amount consumed.\n\n1. **Single Use:** For someone who has only used marijuana once or occasionally, THC can generally be detected in the blood for 1 to 2 days after consumption.\n  \n2. **Moderate to Frequent Use:** For a person who uses marijuana more regularly, THC might be detectable for up to a week or more.\n\n3. **Heavy Use:** For a chronic or heavy user, THC can be detected in the blood for multiple weeks, potentially up to 30 days after cessation of use.\n\nThese durations can fluctuate based on individual differences. It's also important to note that while blood tests can detect THC for these durations, other tests, like urine or hair tests, have different detection windows.",
